\contentsline {table}{\numberline {\relax Table\nobreakspace {\relax 5}.1}{\ignorespaces RLS approximation ratio and lower-bound tightness. Each cell: mean $\pm $ std over $100$ instances. Theoretical worst-case bound: $2-1/m$ ($1.50$ for $m=2$, $1.75$ for $m=4$). All empirical ratios are well below the bound. $\mathrm {OPT}/\mathrm {LB}$ close to $1$ indicates the lower bound is nearly tight.}}{51}{table.caption.10}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {\relax Table\nobreakspace {\relax 5}.2}{\ignorespaces Policy comparison at convergence ($n=8$, $m=2$, $d=3$, $\ell =0.1$). Theoretical MMATPG PoA bound: $(2-1/m)/(1-\ell ) = 1.67$. MARL achieves bounded PoA and high resolution, substantially improving over the no-market greedy baseline. RLS provides the centralized optimum reference.}}{53}{table.caption.17}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {\relax Table\nobreakspace {\relax 5}.3}{\ignorespaces \textbf {[PLACEHOLDER]} Ablation. Metrics at convergence (100 iterations or equivalent compute).}}{55}{table.caption.18}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {\relax Table\nobreakspace {\relax 5}.4}{\ignorespaces Scaling with task graph size $n$. The theoretical PoA bound $(2-1/m)/(1-\ell ) = 1.67$ is independent of $n$; empirical PoA remains well below this bound across all scales. Exploitability increases modestly with $n$ (larger state space is harder to explore) but stays below the convergence threshold. Training time scales polynomially ($\approx O(n^{1.7})$).}}{56}{table.caption.19}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {\relax Table\nobreakspace {\relax 5}.5}{\ignorespaces Scaling with agent count $m$. The theoretical PoA bound increases with $m$ (market friction compounds), but absolute makespan decreases (more parallelism). MARL remains below the bound in all cases.}}{56}{table.caption.20}%
